00:00:14.280 --> 00:00:16.600
or emailed to us by a publicist.

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:20.130
Well, I encourage everyone
to google Dr. Daniel Siegel

00:00:20.130 --> 00:00:21.870
and read about the
schools he attended

00:00:21.870 --> 00:00:23.260
and books he published.

00:00:23.260 --> 00:00:26.750
It is perhaps a better use
of the short time allotted

00:00:26.750 --> 00:00:31.140
for introduction to explain
why it is so exciting to have

00:00:31.140 --> 00:00:36.250
Dr. Siegel here at Google
talking about adolescence.

00:00:36.250 --> 00:00:38.060
The other day, a
friend of mine said

00:00:38.060 --> 00:00:41.020
this about his 16-year-old son.

00:00:41.020 --> 00:00:43.970
Two years ago, he said,
we were best buddies.

00:00:43.970 --> 00:00:47.330
Now all I am to him is a
driver and an a ATM machine.

00:00:49.970 --> 00:00:52.830
Another friend offered the
following pearl of wisdom.

00:00:52.830 --> 00:00:55.760
Yes, teenagers want
nothing to do with you,

00:00:55.760 --> 00:00:57.670
and they can't
wait to leave home.

00:00:57.670 --> 00:00:58.630
But don't worry.

00:00:58.630 --> 00:01:01.850
They'll be back when they're 23.

00:01:01.850 --> 00:01:05.470
These two quotes are typical
of how the grownup world views

00:01:05.470 --> 00:01:09.470
adolescents as inaccessible,
a great big black hole,

00:01:09.470 --> 00:01:11.170
a terrible thing we
need to get through

00:01:11.170 --> 00:01:14.820
as best we can until a grownup
emerges on the other side

00:01:14.820 --> 00:01:18.550
and we can finally breathe
a huge sigh of relief.

00:01:18.550 --> 00:01:21.630
Grownups and adolescents find
each other frustrating and

00:01:21.630 --> 00:01:22.900
infuriating.

00:01:22.900 --> 00:01:25.670
I suspect that some
of you are parents

00:01:25.670 --> 00:01:27.850
who came to this
talk hoping for tips

00:01:27.850 --> 00:01:29.790
on how to handle
their teenagers.

00:01:29.790 --> 00:01:33.180
And yes, Daniel Siegel's
book "Brainstorm"

00:01:33.180 --> 00:01:36.090
provides a richness of
insight and practical advice

00:01:36.090 --> 00:01:37.730
to meet that need.

00:01:37.730 --> 00:01:40.910
But what makes this
book truly revolutionary

00:01:40.910 --> 00:01:45.220
is its insistence that
adolescence is not a problem

00:01:45.220 --> 00:01:48.030
to be tackled but
an opportunity,

00:01:48.030 --> 00:01:51.950
an amazing opportunity to be
cultivated and celebrated.

00:01:51.950 --> 00:01:55.580
Those same brain changes that
can cause so much anguish

00:01:55.580 --> 00:01:58.170
have the potential, if
correctly understood,

00:01:58.170 --> 00:02:00.970
to not only be a source
of great satisfaction

00:02:00.970 --> 00:02:02.790
but in fact to
quote from the book,

00:02:02.790 --> 00:02:05.850
"they can enable adolescents
to go on and lead

00:02:05.850 --> 00:02:09.979
great lives of
adventure and purpose."

00:02:09.979 --> 00:02:12.600
Reading the book, you discover
that the aggravation normally

00:02:12.600 --> 00:02:16.200
associated with adolescence
is an unnecessary cost

00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:18.070
of how we deal with it.

00:02:18.070 --> 00:02:19.960
Furthermore, hallmarks
of adolescence

00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:24.590
are youthful energy, creativity,
passion, original thought,

00:02:24.590 --> 00:02:27.560
and a panache for
social connectivity.

00:02:27.560 --> 00:02:33.860
These are resources that are now
wasted on a gargantuan scale.

00:02:33.860 --> 00:02:35.500
A better understanding
of the brain

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:38.520
can allow adolescents to
make use of these gifts

00:02:38.520 --> 00:02:41.771
towards the making of a better
society and a better world.

00:02:41.771 --> 00:02:43.270
Ladies and gentlemen,
Daniel Siegel.

